# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jenkins
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] For an overview of content in the Jenkins User Handbook, refer to the User Handbook Overview.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Jenkins Pipeline (or simply "Pipeline" with a capital "P") is a suite of plugins which supports implementing and integrating *continuous delivery pipelines* into Jenkins.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] A *continuous delivery (CD) pipeline* is an automated expression of your process for getting software from version control right through to your users and customers.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Every change to your software (committed in source control) goes through a complex process on its way to being released.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] This process involves building the software in a reliable and repeatable manner, as well as progressing the built software (called a "build") through multiple stages of testing and deployment.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] While the syntax for defining a Pipeline, either in the web UI or with a `Jenkinsfile` is the same, it is generally considered best practice to define the Pipeline in a `Jenkinsfile` and check that in to source control.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] A `Jenkinsfile` can be written using two types of syntax — Declarative and Scripted.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Declarative and Scripted Pipelines are constructed fundamentally differently.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Declarative Pipeline is designed to make writing and reading Pipeline code easier, and provides richer syntactical features over Scripted Pipeline syntax.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Many of the individual syntactical components (or "steps") written into a `Jenkinsfile`, however, are common to both Declarative and Scripted Pipeline.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Read more about how these two types of syntax differ in Pipeline concepts and Pipeline syntax overview below.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Jenkins is, fundamentally, an automation engine which supports a number of automation patterns.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Pipeline adds a powerful set of automation tools onto Jenkins, supporting use cases that span from simple continuous integration to comprehensive CD pipelines.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] While Jenkins has always allowed rudimentary forms of chaining Freestyle Jobs together to perform sequential tasks, [4] Pipeline makes this concept a first-class citizen in Jenkins.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] The following concepts are key aspects of Jenkins Pipeline, which tie in closely to Pipeline syntax (refer to the overview below).
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] A Pipeline is a user-defined model of a CD pipeline.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] A Pipeline’s code defines your entire build process, which typically includes stages for building an application, testing it and then delivering it.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Also, a `pipeline` block is a key part of Declarative Pipeline syntax.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] A node is a machine which is part of the Jenkins environment and is capable of executing a Pipeline.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Also, a `node` block is a key part of Scripted Pipeline syntax.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] A `stage` block defines a conceptually distinct subset of tasks performed through the entire Pipeline (e.g.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Fundamentally, a step tells Jenkins *what* to do at a particular point in time (or "step" in the process).
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] For example, to execute the shell command `make`, use the `sh` step: `sh 'make'`.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] When a plugin extends the Pipeline DSL, [1] that typically means the plugin has implemented a new *step*.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] The following Pipeline code skeletons illustrate the fundamental differences between Declarative Pipeline syntax and Scripted Pipeline syntax.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Be aware that both stages and steps (above) are common elements of both Declarative and Scripted Pipeline syntax.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] In Declarative Pipeline syntax, the `pipeline` block defines all the work done throughout your entire Pipeline.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] In Scripted Pipeline syntax, one or more `node` blocks do the core work throughout the entire Pipeline.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Creates a workspace (a directory specific to that particular Pipeline) where work can be done on files checked out from source control.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] **Caution:** Depending on your Jenkins configuration, some workspaces may not get automatically cleaned up after a period of inactivity.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Refer to the tickets and discussion linked from JENKINS-2111 for more information.
[src:jenkins/book-pipeline] Read more about Pipeline syntax on the Pipeline Syntax page.
[src:jenkins/book-using] This chapter contains topics for typical Jenkins users (of all skill levels) about Jenkins usage which is outside the scope of the core Jenkins features: Pipeline and Blue Ocean.
[src:jenkins/book-using] If you want to create and configure a Pipeline project through a `Jenkinsfile` or through Blue Ocean, or you wish to find out more about these core Jenkins features, refer to the relevant topics within the respective Pipeline and Blue Ocean chapters.
[src:jenkins/book-using] If you are a Jenkins administrator and want to know more about managing Jenkins nodes and instances, see Managing Jenkins.
[src:jenkins/book-using] If you are a system administrator and want to learn how to back-up, restore, maintain as Jenkins servers and nodes, see Jenkins System Administration.
[src:jenkins/book-using] For an overview of content in the Jenkins User Handbook, see User Handbook Overview.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:jenkins/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:jenkins/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:jenkins/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:jenkins/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:jenkins/doc] Welcome to the Jenkins user documentation - for people wanting to *use* Jenkins’s existing functionality and plugin features.
[src:jenkins/doc] If you want to extend the functionality of Jenkins by developing your own Jenkins plugins, please refer to the Extend Jenkins (developer documentation).
[src:jenkins/doc] Jenkins is a self-contained, open source automation server which can be used to automate all sorts of tasks related to building, testing, and delivering or deploying software.
[src:jenkins/doc] Jenkins can be installed through native system packages, Docker, or even run standalone by any machine with a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed.
[src:jenkins/doc] This documentation begins with a Guided Tour to help you get up and running with Jenkins and introduce you to Jenkins’s main feature, Pipeline.
[src:jenkins/doc] There are also tutorials geared to developers who want to orchestrate and automate building their project in Jenkins using Pipeline and Blue Ocean.
[src:jenkins/doc] If you’ve never used Jenkins before or have limited Jenkins experience, then the Guided Tour and introductory tutorials are good places to start.
[src:jenkins/doc] If you are looking for more detailed information about using Jenkins, please refer to the User Handbook.
[src:jenkins/doc] Jenkins is a highly extensible product whose functionality can be extended through the installation of plugins.
[src:jenkins/doc] There are a vast array of plugins available to Jenkins.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] The Jenkins project was originally named *Hudson*, and was renamed in 2011 after a dispute with Oracle, which had forked the project and claimed rights to the project name.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] The Oracle fork, *Hudson*, continued to be developed for a time before being donated to the Eclipse Foundation.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Oracle's Hudson is no longer maintained and was announced as obsolete in February 2017.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Around 2007 Hudson became known as a better alternative to Cruise Control and other open-source build-servers.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] At the JavaOne conference in May 2008 the software won the Duke's Choice Award in the Developer Solutions category.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] During November 2010, after the acquisition of Sun Microsystems by Oracle, an issue arose in the Hudson community with respect to the infrastructure used, which grew to encompass questions over the stewardship and control by Oracle.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Negotiations between the principal project contributors and Oracle took place, and although there were many areas of agreement a key sticking point was the trademarked name "Hudson," after Oracle claimed the right to the name and applied for a trademark in December 2010.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] As a result, on January 11, 2011, a call for votes was made to change the project name from "Hudson" to "Jenkins." The proposal was overwhelmingly approved by a community vote on January 29, 2011, creating the Jenkins project.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] On February 1, 2011, Oracle said that they intended to continue development of Hudson, and considered Jenkins a fork rather than a rename.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Jenkins and Hudson therefore continued as two independent projects, each claiming the other was the fork.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] As of June 2019, the Jenkins organization on GitHub had 667 project members and around 2,200 public repositories, compared with Hudson's 28 project members and 20 public repositories with the last update in 2016.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] In 2011, creator Kohsuke Kawaguchi received an O'Reilly Open Source Award for his work on the Hudson/Jenkins project.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] On April 20, 2016, version 2 was released with the *Pipeline* plugin enabled by default.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] The plugin allows for writing build instructions using a domain specific language based on Apache Groovy.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Jenkins replaced Hudson since February 8, 2017 in Eclipse.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] In March 2018 Jenkins X software project for Kubernetes was publicly presented as a Jenkins sub-project, with support for different cloud providers including AWS EKS among others.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Later, Jenkins X became an independent project under the Continuous Delivery Foundation.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] In March 2019, Jenkins joined the Continuous Delivery Foundation, a new subsidiary of the Linux Foundation, as a founding project.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] In August 2020, Jenkins reached the graduated status in the foundation.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Plugins have been released for Jenkins that extend its use to projects written in languages other than Java.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Plugins are available for integrating Jenkins with most version control systems and bug databases.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Many build tools are supported via their respective plugins.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Plugins can also change the way Jenkins looks or add new functionality.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] There are a set of plugins dedicated for the purpose of unit testing that generate test reports in various formats (for example, JUnit bundled with Jenkins, MSTest, NUnit, etc.) and automated testing that supports automated tests.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Builds can generate test reports in various formats supported by plugins (JUnit support is currently bundled) and Jenkins can display the reports and generate trends and render them in the GUI.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Allows configuring email notifications for build results.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Successful build execution following a prior failure, indicating project recovery.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Unstable build after a successful one, indicating a regression.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Provides a standardized API for other plugins to store and retrieve different types of credentials.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Adds the ability to monitor the result of externally executed jobs.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] This plugin allows managing agents (formerly known as slaves) running on *nix machines over SSH.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] It adds a new type of agent launch method.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] This plugin adds Javadoc support to Jenkins.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] This functionality used to be a part of the core, but as of Jenkins 1.431, it was split off into separate plugins.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] The plugin enables the selection of "Publish Javadoc" as a post-build action, specifying the directory where the Javadoc is to be gathered and if retention is expected for each successful build.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] The platform provides a graphical user interface (GUI) to facilitate the scheduling and monitoring of shell scripts, reducing reliance on command-line execution.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Jenkins' security depends on two factors: access control and protection from external threats.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Access control can be customized via two ways: user authentication and authorization.
[src:jenkins/jenkins-software] Protection from external threats such as CSRF attacks and malicious builds is supported as well.
